I used to process ammonite into the gemstone ammolite. It's a highly toxic procedure and you can become sterilized if you come into contact with the compounds too much. Something my boss told me after my first day when I got that goop all over my skin. (I wasn't sterilized, though). Anyway, this is mainly found in The province of Alberta, Canada. Huge deposits could be found on the banks of the Belly River on the Blood Reserve. So First Nations men would come by our shop with the raw materials and the Master Goldsmith would examine them and they'd haggle out a price. A full fossil (this was 15years ago) would go for about $500. After processing, which meant bringing out the opalescence and preserving it for gemstone quality material, we'd usually get about 10-20,000 dollars out of that $500 dollar investment. Generally you don't get preserved fossils with enough opalescence to make something like OP's picture so the fossil is cut up into smaller pieces that find themselves in pendants, rings, etc. There is a finite amount of these things, so it is actually the rarest gemstone in the world and only increasing in price. If you can invest in some quality pieces and haggle out a good price for them you'll have a decent little nest egg in about 20 years. Tldr: super precious stuff.

This is brilliant. We mostly become the person we think we are. Hopefully they will keep these pictures and it will remind them that they aren't destined to be homeless, that there is another way. My Aunty was homeless. We tried to help her but failed. She died on the streets. Alone. Some people experience mental illness or utter isolation and that is a huge factor. My aunt believed she was unworthy of love or respect. These are issues and patterns that are difficult to break, but the fact is, homelessness is a solvable problem. But the way we teach our children and care for them is the bigger challenge. Do we teach them to walk on by? Do we teach them it's the homeless person's own fault? Do we teach the responsibility of a community, a tribe, for it's own people? All tough questions. This photo essay is one drop in the solution, but if we keep adding to it, the situation will slowly transform. Just a few thoughts, sorry if it bored you. Tldr: be good to each other, we are all sons and daughters.

Phantom Menace. When the theatre went dark and that 20th Century Fox music blared, transitioning to the Lucasfilm logo the audience lost their shit with excitement. Die hard fans. We had lined up for over 24 hours for the first midnight showing in our city. This was The Moment. At last. And then the movie began. I'm sure everyone in that theatre was thinking the same thoughts I was..."soon...soon...this is just groundwork. It's going to get better, I know it. Soon..." Then we were 3/4 of the way through the film. It wasn't going to get better. I honestly felt a hollow pit in my chest, a great and horrible empty disappointment. This was what we had waited for? This stinking pile of...god help me...poodoo? I went to watch it again in the theatre with my brother. Both of us were sure we'd gotten it wrong, that maybe we had built it up too much, that our expectations had simply been too high, too unachievable for any movie. A second viewing would show us how great the movie really was, right? Wrong. It was worse. So yeah...Phantom Menace.

This is a great comment. Too bad it's way down in the thread. This is exactly the case with so many roles, and it's why we often think the 'bad guy' in a film was a better actor. A good film has a great antagonist. You need somewhere to direct your passion/fear/hatred so you relate to and journey with the protagonist (Diplomatic Immunity!). Sometimes the best acting is the acting we don't actively 'see'. If we stop thinking about the actor and simply move along with them naturally, then the actor has done their job. They've drawn us into the STORY instead of the ROLE. That being said, was it Leo's best role? I'm sure he thinks so. I have no doubt he poured more of his energy and dedication into this role than any other - except maybe Gilbert Grape, I still don't understand how he managed to play that part so convincingly - and he certainly had a passion for the subject matter. That's a lot of words. Tldr: don't notice 'great acting'? Then it probably was.
